::section{#intro}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Overview of synthetic lattice research and document objectives."
::

# Introduction

The study of quantum flux in synthetic lattices has emerged as a cornerstone of modern condensed matter physics @cite{smith2024}. Unlike natural crystals, synthetic lattices allow for the precise engineering of topological properties.

The fundamental Hamiltonian for such a system is given by:

::equation{#eq-hamiltonian}
$$
H = -t \sum_{\langle i,j \rangle} c_i^\dagger c_j e^{i \phi_{ij}} + U \sum_i n_{i\uparrow} n_{i\downarrow}
$$
::label The Hubbard Model with Complex Hopping
::endequation

Where $t$ represents the hopping amplitude and $\phi_{ij}$ is the synthetic gauge field.

::callout{type="info"}
This document is a demonstration of the `.smd` format capabilities.
::endcallout

::endsection

