depends_on: ["#intro"]
::

# Methodology

We utilize an optical lattice created by three pairs of counter-propagating laser beams. The experimental flow is visualized below:

::diagram{#diag-setup}
::type flowchart
::description
Experimental setup flow: Preparation of the Bose-Einstein Condensate (BEC), 
loading into the optical lattice, and subsequent spectroscopic measurement.
::
```mermaid
graph LR
    A[BEC Preparation] --> B[Lattice Loading]
    B --> C[Phase Stabilization]
    C --> D[Measurement]
    D --> E{Data Valid?}
    E -->|Yes| F[Storage]
    E -->|No| B
```
::enddiagram

::endsection

::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Measurement data and observed flux patterns."
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Experimental Results

Our measurements indicate a strong correlation between lattice depth and flux stability.

::chart{#chart-data}
::title Flux Stability Measurements
::interpretation
The stability index remains high (>0.85) for lattice depths between 5 and 15 Er. 
A sharp drop is observed beyond 20 Er, likely due to increased decoherence.
::
::source Simulation Data - Run #1042
| Depth (Er) | Stability Index | Error Margin |
|---|---|---|
| 5 | 0.92 | ±0.01 |
| 10 | 0.89 | ±0.02 |
| 15 | 0.86 | ±0.01 |
| 20 | 0.74 | ±0.05 |
| 25 | 0.52 | ±0.08 |
::endchart

We also captured the interference patterns using high-resolution imaging:

::figure{#fig-pattern}
::file assets/interference-pattern.png
::description
High-resolution interference pattern captured after a 12ms time-of-flight expansion. 
The hexagonal symmetry reflects the underlying lattice geometry.
::
::interpretation
The sharp peaks confirm the persistence of long-range phase coherence 
across the synthetic lattice.
::
::endfigure

::endsection

::section{#conclusion}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "Final remarks on the stability of quantum flux in artificial systems."
depends_on: ["#results"]
::

# Conclusion

Synthetic lattices provide a robust platform for simulating complex gauge fields. Our results confirm that flux stability is achievable within a wide range of operational parameters.

::endsection
